Since Q and S are selected without replacement, the probabilities are slightly different. Wait, actually, when selecting Q and S without replacement, the joint probability is not independent. For example, the probability that Q is at distance 1 and S is at distance 1 is (5/11) * (4/10) = 20/110. Similarly, the probability that Q is at distance 2 and S is at distance 2 is (5/11) * (4/10) = 20/110. The probability that Q is at distance 3 and S is at distance 3 is (1/11) * (0/10) = 0.
